##Fitness Industry: 10 times more users online, 10 times more money lost each month

Function introduction, the interface news is China has the influence original financial and economic new media, only serves the independent thinking crowd

Photo: UNSPLASH

Reporter: Wu Yangyu Editor: Wen Shuqi

“

The online migration of the fitness industry may be a temporary escape hatch, but when the light comes on, how many entrepreneurs can stand up to the end?

”

Han Jia never mentioned the worst case, and her boss told her she had to get through it this time.

As head of marketing for a chain of gyms, she knows the timing of the reopening is uncertain, but what if it lasts until May or June?

"Frankly speaking, we don't want to face that either. We can only say we'll see how it goes, and now we'll just let it go back to normal in March, " Han Jia told interface news, "If things don't get back to normal by March, maybe we'll take the next step. "

The practical conditions on which the next steps will be based are complex. For example, if the relevant government departments in policy to give more support, rent reduction, tax reduction, then they can continue to go on. "But if not, who knows, " Han said. "everything is unknown. "

In the early 2020s, with COVID-19 pneumonia raging across the country, no one dared venture outside, let alone into a confined space like a gym. Under the instruction of the Municipal Sports Bureau, the gyms in both the community and the business district have all been closed, and the winter of the fitness industry has officially arrived.

But the pain is forcing change, and fitness seems to be finally becoming a national consciousness. In addition to all the acquired protective measures, the autoimmunity becomes a key innate barrier to the virus. Immunity, good health, exercise, these familiar associations, began to appear frequently in the news and in people's mouths.

So far, sports bureaus in Beijing, Shanghai, Harbin, Qinghai and other provinces and cities have issued articles calling on citizens to actively exercise at home during the epidemic prevention and control period, along with complete sports videos or action commentary.

Below that is the online migration of the entire fitness industry. It may be a temporary escape hatch until the epidemic is over, but when it does, what percentage of entrepreneurs will stand out in the end?

###It's hard to get off the grid

After the miserable Spring Festival holiday, the virus is still spreading at an incalculable rate.

On the evening of January 30, Han Jia led the marketing team to rush out the posters, while asking the sales team to send out wechat lists to all members and post the same content to their friends'circles, and at the same time making public account articles to prepare for push, she had to make sure that all 20,000 members were notified.

Han Jia's company will officially close all its stores from Jan. 31 to comply with government regulations on the epidemic and to avoid the risk of possible spread of the disease if it returns to Beijing.

When she first heard about the outbreak, she had no idea it would come to this.

A week ago, the epidemic alert was just sounded across the country. The company's eight stores did not immediately close, but they had to be taken seriously, and step-by-step measures to strengthen the prevention and control: Check Body temperature, every four hours disinfection, requiring everyone to wear masks.

Despite the concerns, the company has traditionally kept four stores open during the official Chinese New Year holiday, "because many of our members also have fitness habits during the Spring Festival, and since we have already committed, we have to give them something. "

At this time there are still people going to the gym -- As many as 50 to 60 people enter a single store every day, the average daily flow is 200 to 300 people, the peak can reach 500 to 600 people.

"It was supposed to be until February 9, but I didn't think it was that serious, " Han said. "I didn't think it would be open any time soon. "

As with all msmes, many of the offline gyms have to support a large family while paying rent to the property. Han Jia did not give specific figures for the company's monthly spending on labor and rent, but its eight stores are in high-traffic business complexes and mid-to-high-end neighborhoods, plus coaching, sales, operations and other functions, there are about 370 employees in the company.

"We may be in this situation, " she said, adding that other companies' cash flow support is generally around two months. "That's about the time, " she said, "I can not give you a definite answer. "

For the implementation of the annual membership system of the gym, in the case of non-member personal reasons can not be business, the gym needs to members according to the closure of extended membership time limit. It may not be a direct loss, but the real pain in the traditional gym is that there will be no new memberships for the next three to five months because there will be no return on fees.

According to the report on market research and investment strategic planning of fitness clubs in China, published by the forward-looking Industry Research Institute, the market size of fitness clubs in China was about 70 billion yuan in 2015 and 87.8 billion yuan in 2017. With a compound annual growth rate of 12% , the market size of Chinese gyms may reach 123 billion yuan by 2020.

According to Han Jia, the company will set its annual fee at 10,000 to 20,000 yuan according to the specifications of each store. In the past, she recalls, each store added an average of 150-200 new members a month, with a renewal rate of about 70 per cent. The simultaneous closure of eight stores means direct losses of around M Yuan a month.

What's more, the Spring Festival is the key fitness industry "blood back period. ".

"A lot of gyms want to be able to turn around after the Spring Festival because there is a big demand at this time, " Han told interface news. "I didn't expect that they would all be photographed back. "

"according to the past performance law of the fitness industry, after the Spring Festival is the main period for fitness venues to increase their performance. Usually February and March account for more than 80 per cent of the first quarter,"Bian Guangming, Qingniao's chairman, said in an interview with the China Youth Daily's China Youth Daily.

A broader wave of shutdowns is spreading, as are new types of gyms, in the form of single-class pay-per-session, small classes, outside the traditional gym.

Keep's gym brand Keepland announced on Jan. 24 that it would close all of its stores in Beijing and Shanghai between Jan. 25 and Feb. 2,2020, and then extended the shutdown to Feb. 9 at the government's request, at the same time, the time limit for the use of all user packs has been extended by 30 days.

Super Orangutan closed its Wuhan store as early as January 21, and has closed other city stores, its resumption of business from February 3 to February 10.

According to our reporter, the Super Ape has made it clear that "we don't expect to be back in business until March 1, and will give notice if there are any special circumstances. " There are no plans to reopen the store.

###Save yourself online

Tt Live broadcast founder Zhang Kang in a recent sharing on the growth rate of live fitness. Tt live broadcast fitness mainly facing the family scene, service female users.

"over the last 15 days, we've had full-time remote overtime, and now we've achieved a 20 percent daily compound user growth, and by the end of Q1, the total number of users should be 10-20 times what it was before, " he said.

To some extent, this confirms the epidemic period from the side of the online fitness industry to revive the possibility.

As early as early as 2019, the Super Orangutan had nearly 80 stores in nine cities, including Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou and Shenzhen, as well as Chengdu and Wuhan. It had just completed a $360 million round of financing, and founder jump said it hoped to add 100 stores in 2019, bringing the total to about 200.

On February 3 this year, the "sports chain guide" released an exclusive interview with jump. While discussing the issue, Tiaokao was still in the mood to return to work on Feb. 10, a week later.

In terms of delayed labor and rental costs, she reckons that if it is scheduled to open on February 10th, it will have fluctuated for 20 days since it closed. For coaches who haven't paid for lessons in nearly a month, the team has decided to minimum wage and offer each coach a $10,000 no interest loan as a working capital; rent is being negotiated with some developers.

The big surprise, she says, came online. At this time, the Super Orangutan in a live broadcast platform on the line, "Super Orangutan home squatting" live program, by the coach to lead the user to do simple shape and aerobic exercise. "The number of people who signed up temporarily for the first live broadcast exceeded 170,000 at the same time, making it the top 1 anchor on the live broadcast, " Tiaodao said.

"right now we're not thinking about making money online, but we're thinking about turning live streaming into a long-term service that delivers value to users, " she said at the time

Apparently, that changed very quickly.

On February 10, the official public account of the Super Orangutan launched a course product, "super orangutan stay at home-14 days 'accompany' training camp. ". Its content is 14 antenna training, 320 minutes custom challenge training, February 17 the first session, price 399 yuan.

According to the reporter, the product a total of 22 coaches February 17 to March 1 of the course, have all been full. According to the upper limit of 30 people per class, 399 yuan per person cost calculation, a total of more than 260,000 yuan income. That's not much compared to the average super chimp's 100 yuan per class fee, but it does open up a small cash hole.

In fact, depending on the nature of each company's business, fitness brands have different goals for online self-help.

The company has no significant cash flow pressure at the moment, Keep told interface news. The temporary closure of the Keepland business line, which in the past ranked lower than the sports consumer brands, online advertising and membership, so the impact on the company's overall revenue is not significant.

Still, Keep is actively running three things online.

First, on January 31, Keep launched a syndication page on the APP, featuring 11 brands including daily Yoga, Lululemon, morning, Shape, and more, by the brand's coaches or sports master classes, at the same time there are yoga, aerobics and other forms of optional.

According to Keep share, as of February 5, the total number of viewers for all courses was more than 56.5 million, while the online population peaked at 160,000.

Second, Keep has partnered with State General Administration of Sports to launch an anti epidemic guide. The page differs from the previous one in that it features video lectures and is relatively basic in movement, reaching people who want simple movement but are not used to live streaming.

Both live and video are currently free, and live-streaming sessions will continue until at least the end of February, Keep said. All of the Keepland coaches participating in the class will convert their live broadcast hours into class fees.

In addition to the "public good" project, Keep is launching a new business.

Keep's PR director, Li Ruoming, told interface news that companies such as big Internet companies, technology IT companies and fast food brands have approached them to negotiate a partnership by offering their employees a sports punch card page, for corporate oversight. "It's going to be an ERP aggregation page, aggregating the company's demands for employee training and other requirements. "

It is reported that there have been 30 to 40 enterprises expressed the business communication intention. "It's still docking, so it should be a while before the project starts, " Li said. "In fact, the significance of brand cooperation is much greater, and commercialization has not been decided yet. "

At a particular time, the benefits of the Internet's DNA began to show up in product forms like Keep and super gorilla. Whether it's aggregation traffic, brand communication, or testing the waters of a new form of content payment, everything is possible.

For the traditional form of gym, the short-term access to the online revenue is difficult, was not in their plans, the intention to maintain customer relations more. Han Jia told reporters that the company is currently doing health knowledge lectures in various wechat groups, coaches shoot fitness video upload platform, while participating in the video site live fitness broadcast.

"In fact, the purpose of our live broadcast is not only for traffic, nor for brand communication, " Han said. "It's also to give members a [ exercise ] opportunity to connect with them. "

###That the future is finally here?

During the 15 days of the outbreak, Zhang Kang, founder of TT live, said it was like 15 months, "very busy" . He was referring to the massive influx of projects and resources.

This may be a national fitness awareness of the most intense period, but the industry is clear, in fact, live fitness to fully attract users is not easy.

After the launch of "super home stay at home" , Tiaodao shared many details about the adjustment of the product, "For example, on the first day there were a lot of ground movements, many people said that their mobile phones were too small to see clearly and inconvenient, and on the second day we reduced the ground movements. Considering the fact that they were all at home, the butt-raising course combined with a cloth and the floor was also cleaned while working out. The coach would also wear a house uniform to create an atmosphere. "

In addition, the team will add some square dance-style music, so that parents and other elders can also join the movement; under the influence of the pet will be infected with the virus rumors, also included in the course of the weight-bearing training with dogs and cats.

In the long run, all content payment will encounter a series of matching, balance supply and demand relationship of common problems. For example, a coach may have to overcome the emptiness of a live broadcast to find the feeling and skill of interacting closely with a user in front of the camera, or a user may have difficulty sticking with a single scene for a long time.

So when the epidemic is over, will live streaming become a more common form of fitness product? Li ruoming told the interface news reporter that he could not rule out the possibility of embedding the live broadcast into the APP in the future.

"But if it's after the epidemic, maybe we need to evaluate whether people are more interested in live streaming, or whether it's Keepland itself, or the old-fashioned follow-up course, and we need to look at some operational data, " Li said, "there is no thinking about doing commercial payments at this stage. "

It may be too early to think about making money, but if you're serious about online fitness, it's not just about the product itself, it's about the customer, the diversion, the transformation. Zhang Kang from a more practical point of view, said the current flow of dividends can still be used.

"For example, Douyin and Toutiao, this is the first-line Echelon, and at this time the sun is at its zenith, so it's not possible to talk about cooperation with them. But the industry has such short-video live platforms as the second-line echelon and the third-line Echelon, and they are extremely short of content, " Zhang said, "The first-line echelon platform we can also do, in the short term is to earn a call, but in the long term can be realized, can not say diversion. Private domain must be closer to the transaction link, if your private domain and the transaction link jump many times, even do not give you jump link, then the accumulated private domain efficiency is very low."

From all sides, the trend on the migration line is more of a delaying tactic for brands that focus on physical businesses, allowing them to retain users and observe opportunities. For companies such as Keep, which has a history of leaning online, the current period seems to test their ability to marshal resources and come up with solutions. With data to back it up, this could be an important time to consolidate user loyalty and attract advertisers.

At this point, as important as survival is confidence in the industry.

"I think it's a particularly heavy blow for the fitness industry, " Han said, "because the fitness industry itself depends on cash flow, some gyms can not be maintained once the funding chain breaks, so the whole industry is more anxious. "

But despite his anxiety, Han said he has not lost confidence.

"It must have been a boom in fitness demand after that, " she said, "because people will think that health is the most important thing, to improve their resistance and immunity, how to improve, is not exercise? So there will be more people willing to invest in this. "

The leap of the super-ape suggests, "Frankly speaking, before the outbreak, the whole fitness industry was in a period of adjustment, and I think more and more companies are getting better and becoming service-driven and focusing on coaches, content and courses. As peers, I think we should stick together to keep warm, not fight amongst ourselves and drive up prices."

"In the end, I'm optimistic, " she said. "after all, grief is useless. "

(Han Jia is a pseudonym)
